[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(5) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Standing in the synagogues.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The Jewish custom, more or less prevalent throughout the East, and for a time retained at certain seasons in the Christian Church, was to pray standing, with outstretched, uplifted hands, and there was nothing in the attitude as such that made it an act of ostentatious devotion; nor would there have been any ostentation in thus joining in the common prayer of the congregation assembled in the synagogue. What our Lord’s words point to, was the custom of going into the synagogue, as men go now into the churches of Latin Christendom, to offer private devotion (as, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "e.g.,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in the parable of the Pharisee and the publican), and of doing this so as to attract notice, the worshipper standing apart as if absorbed in prayer, while secretly glancing round to watch the impression which he might be making on others who were looking on.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In the corners of the streets.—Not the same word as in Matthew 6:3, but the broad, open places of the city. There, too, the Pharisees might be seen, reciting their appointed prayers—probably the well-known eighteen acts of devotion which were appointed for the use of devout Israelites—and with the tallith or veil of prayer over their head.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "In the corners of the streets.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Not the same word as in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 6:3",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", but the broad, open places of the city. There, too, the Pharisees might be seen, reciting their appointed prayers—probably the well-known eighteen acts of devotion which were appointed for the use of devout Israelites—and with the ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "tallith",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " or veil of prayer over their head.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
